The paper discusses Sum-Product Networks (SPNs), which are a type of deep probabilistic model used for density estimation and inference. This makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper focuses on visualizing and understanding the inner workings of SPNs, which suggests it may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) and Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes criteria for extracting representations from SPNs, which is a common topic in Neural Networks (cs.NE) research.
